    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "AAAA9H///80\u003d",
        "filename": "android/console-client.c",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 68,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2010-11-15T11:11:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think it would be clearer if the code could be written in a more \"linear\" fashion. It\u0027s hard to understand what\u0027s going on there. Also, please add debug messages in case of errors, we\u0027re likely going to see very weird network setups and these will be helpful to understand why connections can\u0027t be made properly. E.g.:\n\ndo {\n  // Try to connect, with a timeout\n  status \u003d socket_connect(fd, sockaddr);\n  if (status \u003c 0) {\n    if (errno !\u003d EINPROGRESS) {\n      D(\"%s: Could not connect %s\", __FUNCTION__, errno_str);\n      break;\n    }\n    iolooper_add_write(looper, fd);\n    status \u003d iolooper_wait(loop,er CORE_PORT_TIMEOUT_MS);\n    if (status \u003c\u003d 0) {\n        D(\"%s: Could not connect: %s\", __FUNCTION__, errno_str);\n        break;\n    }\n    iolooper_del_write(iolooper, fd);\n  }\n\n  // Read the handshake message, with a timeout\n  iolooper_add_read(looper, fd);\n  status \u003d iolooper_wait(looper, CORE_PORT_TEIMOUT_MS);\n  if (status \u003c\u003d 0) {\n    D(\"%s: Could not read console handshake: %s\",\n        __FUNCTION__, errno_str);\n    break;\n  }\n  if (!iolooper_is_read(looper, fd)) {\n    D(\"%s: Internal error, iolooper_is_read() not set!\", __FUNCTION__);\n    break;\n  }\n\n  /* Read first line and check content */\n  int read_bytes \u003d read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf));\n  if (read_bytes \u003c 0) {\n    D(\"%s: Could not read console handshake: %s\\n\", __FUNCTION__, errno_str);\n    break;\n  }\n  if (read_bytes \u003c 15 || memcmp(buf, \"Android Console\", 15)) {\n    D(\"%s: Bad Android console handshake: \u0027%.*s\u0027\", __FUNCTION__, read_bytes, buf);\n    break;\n  }\n  ...\n\n  // Success\n  iolooper_free(looper);\n  return fd;\n\n} while (0)\n\n// Failure.\niolooper_free(looper);\nclose(fd);\nreturn -1;",
      "revId": "42fe6c709273d6b62e31e1a0d7bde9e9124f9b45",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "AAAA9H///8w\u003d",
        "filename": "android/console-client.c",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 72,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2010-11-15T11:11:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "doubling the timeout value for te connect + read + optional second read is not elegant. It might be better to introduce new functions in iolooper.h, e.g.:\n\nint64_t iolooper_now(); which returns the current time in millseconds as an int64_t (obtained with gettimeofday())\n\nint iolooper_wait_absolute(iolooper_t, int64_t), which waits with an absolute time.\n\nThen the code would do something like:\n\nint64_t deadline \u003d iolooper_now() + CORE_PORT_TIMEOUT_MS;\n\nand all waits would be:\n\niolooper_wait_absolute(looper, deadline);\nA return value of 0 would be interpreted as a time-out (we could even set errno to ETIMEDOUT in this case).\n\nWe could also introduce a function to read a line char-by-char terminated by \\r\\n (or simply \\n) from the socket with an absolute deadline into a fixed-size buffer (with a loop), then simply perform two reads. That would make the code more robust.",
      "revId": "42fe6c709273d6b62e31e1a0d7bde9e9124f9b45",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
